He was the founder of Disneyland, California, a theme park that was enormously successful and one of the best-known tourist attractions in the world.

Disney began his artistic career at age 18 by drawing political caricatures for a newspaper in Kansas City. From there he went on to draw comic strips for newspapers in Chicago. Their first major success came with Steamboat Willie (1928), which introduced Mickey Mouse to audiences around the world. This was followed by a series of popular animated films including Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs (1937), Pinocchio (1940), Fantasia (1940), Dumbo (1941) and Bambi (1942).

In addition to producing feature films, Disney also produced television shows such as The Mickey Mouse Club and Davy Crockett. In 1955 he opened Disneyland theme park in Anaheim, California which quickly became one of the most popular tourist attractions in the world. In 1965 he began work on EPCOT (Experimental Prototype Community Of Tomorrow) but passed away before its completion in 1982. Today Walt Disney is remembered as one of America's most influential filmmakers who helped shape modern entertainment culture with his groundbreaking work in animation and theme parks.
